body:
Pattern matching was another idea I had for syntax for use cases like this. That might also be useful for user-defined functions/methods that act like var_export.

This would let you make types depend on a combination of parameters, and avoids needing templates except when necessary.

There's also the question of what to do if the caller passes through a `?string` - I assume both proposals would infer `string|array<string, string>`, and have equivalent functionality with different syntax.

```php
/**
 * @param mixed $expression
 * @psalm-return-matching (false $return) void
 * @psalm-return-matching (true $return) string
 */
function var_export($expression, bool $return = false) {
    // ...
}
```

```php
    /**
     * @return string|string[]
     * @psalm-return-matching (string $name) string
     * @psalm-return-matching (null $name) array<string, string>
     */
    public function getAttribute(?string $name, string $default = '')
    {
       if (null === $name) {
            return $this->itemAttr;
        }
        return isset($this->itemAttr[$name]) ? $this->itemAttr[$name] : $default;
    }
```

How about using substitution with `callable`?

```
@psalm-match callable (T1, T2=): T3
@psalm-match callable (T4, T5): T6
function foo($a, $b) {
    // ...
}
```

That means that the `@psalm-match` takes priority (when matched) over the type of `foo` that is inferred from its signature.

Effectively, it's method overloading.

EDIT: the above would be very similar to what already works in type annotations, so generics & co would be compatible. What's tricky is having multiple definitions for a call: each callable would become an intersection type...

```php
/**
 * @param mixed $expression
 * @psalm-match callable(mixed, true) : string
 * @psalm-match callable(mixed, bool=) : void
 */
function var_export($expression, bool $return = false) {
    // ...
}
```

@Ocramius In the proposed syntax those would become

```php
/**
 * @template TReturnFlag as bool
 * @param mixed $expression
 * @param TReturnFlag $return
 * @psalm-return (TReturnFlag is true ? string : void)
 */
function var_export($expression, bool $return = false) {
    // ...
}
```
and
```php
/**
 * @template T as int|float
 * @param T $a
 * @param T $b
 * @return int|float
 * @psalm-return (T is int ? int : float)
 */
function add($a, $b) {
    return $a + $b;
}
```

I think those are both a little easier to understand

